properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A frontal system over the BC north coast will move southward tonight and Monday. By Monday afternoon the system will reach West Vancouver Island and upwards of 100 to 200 mm of rain could fall through Tuesday morning. Over the south coast, the frontal system will become entrenched overnight Monday and through Tuesday afternoon. During that time, rainfall amounts of 50 to 75 mm could occur over most of Metro Vancouver, the Fraser Valley, Howe Sound, as well as East Vancouver Island between Nanoose Bay and Fanny Bay. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Maximum gusts: southwesterly 80 km/h, except 110 along parts of the coast. Locations: northern Newfoundland. Time span: overnight Monday until Tuesday morning. Remarks: Anyone who has Halloween decorations outdoors should consider bringing them inside, as they are at risk of being tossed by the wind. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Ice build-up due to freezing rain is expected or occurring. A nearly stationary area of mixed precipitation will provide a prolonged period of freezing rain and ice pellets beginning Sunday night. Freezing rain amounts will be highly variable, but should generally range from 1-5 mm. The highest freezing rain amounts are expected to stay near and south of Fort Chipewyan, and north of La Loche. This warning will likely be expanded eastwards Monday morning. The freezing rain and ice pellets are forecast to end Monday night. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A prolonged period of snow, ice pellets, and freezing rain is expected to tonight and end Monday afternoon. The heaviest snow is expected to fall near the Alberta-N.W.T. border, with total accumulations of 10-15 cm possible. A persistent band of freezing rain and ice pellets is expected to form south of the snow. There is uncertainty on the exact location of the band of freezing rain, but current indications suggest it will be mainly south of Highway 58. Freezing rain amounts will be highly variable, but could range from 1-5 mm. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.
